o hundred mostly Protestant and Catholic men and women who were born in the 1920s and interviewed in adolescence, and again in the 1950s, 1970s, 1980s, and late 1990s. Woven throughout with rich, intimate life stories, the book presents and analyzes a wide range of data from this study on the participants' religious and spiritual journeys. A testament to the vibrancy of religion in the United States, In the Course of a Lifetime provides an illuminating and sometimes surprising perspective on how individual lives have intersected with cultural change throughout the decades of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFaith development. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  a1920s.  a20th century.  aamerica.  aamerican religion.  acatholics.  achristian history.  achristianity.  acomparative religion.  acultural change.  ademographic study.  afaith and religion.  alife stories.  along term study.  anonfiction.  apersonal growth.  apersonal journey.  aprotestants.  areligion and culture.  areligious belief.  areligious experiences.  areligious lifestyles.  areligious practices.  areligious scholars.  areligious studies.  arole of religion.  aspiritual journey.  aspirituality.  atheology.  aus religion.1 aWink, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024901140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094003140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940031/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY